<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#00ff00">Originally posted by darkangelx on 12-18-2001 08:51 AM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">well this is how I have mine setup:

3 comps 2 windoze 1 slackware
1 netgear 10/100mb switch
broadband

modem and all 3 comps plugged in

routing:

static ip on linux box with 2 ips assigned to 1 nic (yes yes i know im ghetto but it works)

my ifconfig looks like this:
eth0      Link encap:Ethernet  *HWaddr (removed)
         **inet addr:192.0.1.1  Bcast:192.0.0.255 Mask:255.255.255.0
          UP BROADCAST RUNNING MULTICAST  MTU:1500  Metric:1
          RX packets:4163506 errors:0 dropped:0 overruns:0 frame:0
          TX packets:4269409 errors:0 dropped:0 overruns:0 carrier:0
          collisions:1435 txqueuelen:100
          RX bytes:526692873 (502.2 Mb)  TX bytes:566613407 (540.3 Mb)
          Interrupt:11 Base address:0xec00

eth0:0    Link encap:Ethernet  HWaddr (removed)
          inet addr:192.0.0.2 Bcast:192.0.0.255  Mask:255.255.255..0
          UP BROADCAST RUNNING MULTICAST  MTU:1500  Metric:1
          Interrupt:11 Base address:0xec00

lo        Link encap:Local Loopback
          inet addr:127.0.0.1  Mask:255.0.0.0
          UP LOOPBACK RUNNING  MTU:3924  Metric:1
          RX packets:22 errors:0 dropped:0 overruns:0 frame:0
          TX packets:22 errors:0 dropped:0 overruns:0 carrier:0
          collisions:0 txqueuelen:0
          RX bytes:1408 (1.3 Kb)  TX bytes:1408 (1.3 Kb)

windoz box 1

ip 192.0.0.3
subnet 255.255.255.0
gateway 192.0.0.2

windoz box 2

ip 192.0.0.4
subnet 255.255.255.0
gateway 192.0.0.2

*changed just in case 
**notice that the ip on the static eth0 is on another subnet than eth0:0, but eth0:0 is on the same subnet as the 2 windoz boxes which allows them to see each other and route accordingly even with a switch because im forcing the connection through the slackware box.  This is just one possible way to do it if your linux box has only 1 nic but many people have advised against this because it can cause collisions on the network and bad throughput *cough* whatever, yes i have seen some collisions but nothing too noticable but my speed doesnt suffer (pull files from either windoz box @ 1.2-1.4mb/s).

Dunno if this confuses you or helps, but its what i did...</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
